    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1951-02-13T19:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1951-02-13T19:00:00-05:00" n="719"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d719">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">876.00 <gloss target="#t_TA1">TA</gloss>/1–2551:
                    Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">Embassy in Liberia</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d719fn1">This telegram was drafted by <persName
                            corresp="#p_SH1">Sims</persName> (<gloss target="#t_NEA1"
                            >NEA</gloss>/<gloss target="#t_AF1">AF</gloss>), was cleared by
                            <persName corresp="#p_MOW1">Meier</persName> (<gloss target="#t_NEA1"
                            >NEA</gloss>/<gloss target="#t_AF1">AF</gloss>) and <persName
                            corresp="#p_GSJ1">Gorlitz</persName> (<gloss target="#t_ED1"
                        >ED</gloss>), and was approved also by <persName corresp="#p_CLG1"
                            >Cyr</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_BEH1">Bourgerie</persName>
                            (<gloss target="#t_NEA1">NEA</gloss>/<gloss target="#t_AF1"
                        >AF</gloss>).</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1951-02-13T19:00:00-05:00"
                            >February 13, 1951—7 p. m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>112. Dept considers 20% to be set aside by <gloss target="#t_LibGovt1"
                        >LibGovt</gloss> to be <gloss target="#t_Lib1">Lib</gloss>s fair share
                    contribution toward overall technical and financial assistance programs.
                    Interest payments on loans obtained to fin overall program wld be considered by
                    US Govt as legitimate charge against <gloss target="#t_Lib1">Lib</gloss> 20%
                    fair share contribution. <gloss target="#t_Eximbank1">Ex-Im Bank</gloss> Loan
                    Agreement not appropriate document in which to spell out items which US Govt
                    considers acceptable developmental expenditures.</p>
                <p>Dept suggests Joint Comm make recommendations items which it considers legitimate
                    credits against <gloss target="#t_Lib1">Lib</gloss> 20%. Emb Desp 249, Jan
                        25,<note n="2" xml:id="d719fn2">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_1285">p. 1285</ref>.</note>
                    causes Dept concern because implication Joint Comm recommendations may be
                    ignored or lightly brushed aside. While Dept appreciates Joint Comm role
                    advisory unless otherwise specifically provided its views and recommendations
                    shld carry great weight with both <gloss target="#t_LibGovt1">LibGovt</gloss>
                    and US Govt. You may assure Pres <persName corresp="#p_TWVS1">Tubman</persName>
                    substantial majority Joint Comm recommendations crediting interest payments
                    against <gloss target="#t_Lib1">Lib</gloss> 20% will encounter no objection US
                        Govt.<note n="3" xml:id="d719fn3">Telegram 171, February 16, from Monrovia,
                        reported that President <persName corresp="#p_TWVS1">Tubman</persName> was
                        completely satisfied with the Department of State’s assurance regarding the
                        20 percent. (876.00–<gloss target="#t_TA1">TA</gloss>/2–1651)</note>
                </p>
                <p>In absence <gloss target="#t_Amb1">Amb</gloss> (<gloss target="#t_Embtel1"
                        >Embtel</gloss> 150, Jan 22<note n="4" xml:id="d719fn4">Not printed. In it
                        the Embassy requested information regarding the American members of the
                        Joint Commission envisaged in the December 22, 1950, U.S.-Liberian agreement
                        on technical assistance. (876.00 <gloss target="#t_TA1">TA</gloss>/1–2251)
                        Regarding the technical assistance agreements, see the editorial note, <ref
                            target="#pg_1274">p. 1274</ref>.</note>) Chargé d’Affaires will assume
                    ex-officio role on Joint Comm. Dept understands <persName corresp="#p_HCR1"
                        >Hill</persName>, Poindexter, <persName corresp="#p_PFE1">Pinder</persName>,
                    and Reeves [<hi rend="italic">
                        <persName corresp="#p_RJH1">Rives</persName>?</hi>] will serve as US Reps on
                    Joint Comm. Dept approves these designations, and you authorized inform <gloss
                        target="#t_LibGovt1">LibGovt</gloss> accordingly.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_MOW1">Meier</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_HCR1"
                        >Hill</persName> arriving <gloss target="#t_Lib1">Lib</gloss> Feb 16.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_ADG1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Acheson</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
